Summary

This box is centred around a machine that has already been “compromised” previously by a hacker. Once we can execute code on the box, we can use what the hacker has left behind to escalate to root.

Foothold features finding credentials to the administrator panel in a backup after fuzzing the domain and then bypassing disabled php functions to allow code execution via a webshell.

We can get a better shell on the box after this. Using the webshell, we use more credentials we found in the backup to allow us to execute code in mysql and we find that the hacker has left behind a user-defined function in the database that allows code execution through bash. Using this, we can write our public ssh key to authorized_keys to get a better shell through ssh.

Root and user can be done at the same time. After getting a better shell on the box, we find another backdoor has been put in place to allow escalation to root via a modified shared object file which we can reverse to find the password to the backdoor.

Getting a shell

The intended and unintended methods

There are two paths for getting a shell on this box. One is to execute sql commands to find a function named exec_cmd which acts as a backdoor left by the previous hacker. The alternative (unintended) method is to bypass the disabled php functions to get a pseudoshell where you can then issue commands to mysql to find the same exec_cmd and then both paths merge.

I can now try to use one of the exploits I found earlier:

Offensive Security’s Exploit Database Archive

I try this but get “Sorry something went wrong”. After trying further to get it to work, I try manually doing the exploit but this doesn’t work either. I decide to upload a simple php file that should not have any functions banned:

After changing this value, I can browse to http://compromised.htb/shop/vqmod/xml/upload.php and see it worked!:

Reversing the file

Downloading the file, I can open in ghidra to have a closer look. I just select all analyzers since I don’t mind about the prototype functions. Looking at any defined strings, I don’t see anything obvious, so I search pwned and similar terms to see if they’ve left any traces. One search seemed pretty useful, backdoor :

Looking closer at that function, I can see that there are backdoor variables inline with what appears to be a check against a string:

The main comparison is:


iVar2 = strcmp((char *)p,backdoor);

Which we can see as:

So the two variables are seen to be moved into RAX. We can then see the value of RAX being moved to the address of [RSP + backdoor[0]] which will be the first half of the variable and then [RSP + backdoor[8]] which will be the second half of the variable. This makes sense since a qword is 8 bytes so we will need to do this multiple times to move the value since it’s larger than what can fit in one go. Once we’ve moved it, the program will access this value so that it can be compared against the input that the user entered as the password.

It checks the input against whatever the backdoor variable is first. If the entered password matches the backdoor password, we will skip the actual password verification.

Notice that the nested if statement won’t be necessary if our password matches the backdoor password meaning we don’t need to know the root password since it can be bypassed.

There is a call to _unix_verify_password which I assume is the actual password verification and the previous code was added as a backdoor.

As seen before, there are two variables in the decompilation:

But these will be loaded as one for the password comparison as explained previously.

I cannot read either in their current form so I try converting them through ghidra’s inbuilt tool:

I repeat this for the other value:

Strings are terminated by a null byte which can be seen in the picture above \x00 so we know exactly where the string stops. Now have the full value zlke~U3Env82m2- which should mean that I can enter this which will bypass the actual password check and allow me to become root user.
